  <ul>
    <li>
      <p>
        Let <m>f:[a,b]\to\bb R</m> be bounded.
        Then <m>f</m> is integrable if and only if for all <m>\eps>0</m> there exists a partition <m>P_{\eps}</m> of <m>[a,b]</m> such that
        <me>
          U(f,P_{\eps})-L(f,P_{\eps})&#x3C;\eps\text{.}
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        If <m>f:[a,b]\to\bb R</m> is integrable, then there exists a sequence of partitions of <m>[a,b]</m> for which
        <me>
          \limit{n\to\infty}[U(f,P_{n})-L(f,P_{n})]=0\text{.}
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Continuous functions are integrable.
        The proof relies on uniform continuity, which is why compactness and uniform continuity were covered in this chapter.
      </p>
    </li>

